serve.md
     1‚Üí# The serve command
     3‚ÜíThe serve command is used to preview a book by serving it via HTTP at
     4‚Üí`localhost:3000` by default: 
     5‚Üí
     6‚Üí```bash
     7‚Üímdbook serve
     8‚Üí```
     9‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
    27‚Üí### Server options
    29‚ÜíThe `serve` hostname defaults to `localhost`, and the port defaults to `3000`. Either option can be specified on the command line:
    30‚Üí
    31‚Üí```bash
    32‚Üímdbook serve path/to/book -p 8000 -n 127.0.0.1 
    33‚Üí```
    34‚Üí
test.md
     1‚Üí# The test command
     3‚ÜíWhen writing a book, you sometimes need to automate some tests. For example,
     4‚Üí[The Rust Programming Book](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/book/) uses a lot
     5‚Üíof code examples that could get outdated. Therefore it is very important for
     6‚Üíthem to be able to automatically test these code examples.
     7‚Üí
     8‚ÜímdBook supports a `test` command that will run all available tests in a book. At
     9‚Üíthe moment, only Rust tests are supported.
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
watch.md
     1‚Üí# The watch command
     3‚ÜíThe `watch` command is useful when you want your book to be rendered on every
     4‚Üífile change. You could repeatedly issue `mdbook build` every time a file is
     5‚Üíchanged. But using `mdbook watch` once will watch your files and will trigger a
     6‚Üíbuild automatically whenever you modify a file; this includes re-creating
     7‚Üídeleted files still mentioned in `SUMMARY.md`!
     8‚Üí
